1 Introduction

OMICsPCA is a pipeline designed to integrate and analyze heterogeneous multiple assays, factors, data types or modalities (e.g. ChIP-seq, RNA-seq) from multiple sources ( e.g. multiple cell lines, time points). It guides the user through various analyses to decide similar variables (e.g.Cell lines), followed by a selection of assays that should be included in or excluded out from the integration process. The selected assays can be further integrated and analysed and the data points or individuals (e.g. genes, TSSs, exons) may be clustered on the basis of the integrated data coming from single or multiple assays.

Integration of experimental data from multiple sources helps us to understand the origin of variation among the sources being integrated. Moreover, if the data from the same sources are not available, it is not possible to compare such experiments on the same data point. For example, we want to cluster similar genes on the basis of CpG methylation and H3k4me3 histone modification, and we have the following experiments:

  1. CpG methylation on 5 Cell lines A, B, C, D, and E
  2. H3k4me3 histone modification on 10 Cell lines A,D,E,I,K,Q,P,Z,W and G.

Here, we can not do the intended clustering since the Cell lines and the number of cell lines are different in the two experiments. But if CpG of 5 cells are integrated into 1 common metric and H3k4me3 for 10 Cells are integrated into 1 common metric, then it is possible to cluster the genes on the basis of this 2 matrices.

For such similar cases, OMICsPCA is a good tool for data integration and analysis. It can integrate the cell lines into various linear combinations using PCA and identify the most similar cell types on the basis of an assay and thus can overcome data insufficiency.

OMICsPCA can be used in cluster genes, TSSs, exons on the basis of multiple types of heterogeneous experimental or theoretical information or vice-versa. Such kind of multivariate analyses is useful in identification of similar cell lines or assays prior to the integration process. In this vignette, we show an example of the entire analysis process done on human transcription start sites.

3 Example

3.1 Preparation of data

OMICsPCA has an inbuild function prepareDataset() that merges the factors (e.g. CAGE, H3k4me1 etc) corresponding to each annotation (eg. gene, TSS, exon etc.) and from each cell lines into a dataframe and returns this dataframe. The rows of this returned dataframe contain the annotations and each column contain the values of a factors of a cell.

The arguments taken by this function is described below:

  1. factdir : full path of the directory containing files corresponding to various cell lines in .bed format. This directory should contain only the files of same assay (e.g. H3k9ac).

  2. annofile : full path of the file containing the annotation file (e.g exons, TSSs, genes etc) in .bed format

  3. annolist : name of full set or subset of the entries in annotation file.

The .bed files should have at least 4 columns. The first column is the chromosome name, the second and third is the start and end of the feature (e.g. a gene or a ChIP-seq peak etc) accordingly and the fourth column contains the value (e.g. expression of a gene, ChIP-seq intensity of a peak or name of a gene etc.). Some examples of .bed files are shown below :

Here we show the use of prpareDataset() by integrating H2az ChIP-seq peaks from 5 cell lines into a data frame named “H2az”. The example data sets are packaged inside the OMICsPCAdata package

anno <- system.file("extdata/annotation/TSS_groups.bed",
package = "OMICsPCAdata")

list <- system.file("extdata/annotation/GENCODE_list",
package = "OMICsPCAdata")

fact <- system.file("extdata/factors/H2az",
package = "OMICsPCAdata")

list.files(path = fact)
# [1] "Gm12878.bed" "Hepg2.bed"   "Hsmm.bed"    "K562.bed"    "Osteobl.bed"

prepareDataset() will combine these 5 cell lines into a dataframe (name should be supplied through factname). The rows of the dataframe will correspond to the entries in the variable named list and the columns will correspond to the 5 cell lines shown above.


H2az_all_cells <- prepareDataset(factdir = fact,
annofile = anno, annolist = list)

head(H2az_all_cells, n = 4)

 

3.2 Reading data

OMICsPCA is designed to read various assays done on various cell lines into an user defined S4 variale and then run various analyses on this object. The class of this S4 object is predefined as OMICS and a contructor function in this name is provided to create an object of class OMICS. For ease of analysis we compiled some preloaded data similar to the output of prepareData() into the supporting package OMICsPCAdata().

The data is read to the InputAssays slot of the “OMICS” object by the function InputOMICs. It can read object diresctly from the environment or from file.

3.2.1 Reading from objects

If the objects are present in the global environment, we can directly read them.

library(OMICsPCAdata)

# creating an object of class "OMICs" using the constructor
#function OMICS()

OMICsdata <- OMICs()

str(OMICsdata)
# Formal class 'OMICs' [package "OMICsPCA"] with 4 slots
#   ..@ InputAssays  : list()
#   ..@ groups       : list()
#   ..@ PCA          : list()
#   ..@ integratedPCA: list()

Assays <- c("CAGE_Cell_wise_v2",
            "CpG_methylation_Cell_wise",
            "DHS_len_Cell_wise",
            "H2az_Cell_wise",
            "H3k27ac_Cell_wise",
            "H3k27me3_Cell_wise",
            "H3k4me1_Cell_wise",
            "H3k4me2_Cell_wise",
            "H3k4me3_Cell_wise",
            "H3k79me2_Cell_wise",
            "H3k9ac_Cell_wise",
            "H3k9me3_Cell_wise",
            "H4k20me1_Cell_wise")

### reading data into OMICsdata object
InputOMICs(name = "OMICsdata", Assays = Assays)

 

3.2.2 Reading from files

To read from file we need to pass to additional argument path and typeisfile. By default typeisfile is set to FALSE and needs to be changed to TRUE in order to read from file. path should contain the path to the directory containing files to be read.

Assays <- c("CAGE_Cell_wise_v2",
            "CpG_methylation_Cell_wise",
            "DHS_len_Cell_wise",
            "H2az_Cell_wise",
            "H3k27ac_Cell_wise",
            "H3k27me3_Cell_wise",
            "H3k4me1_Cell_wise",
            "H3k4me2_Cell_wise",
            "H3k4me3_Cell_wise",
            "H3k79me2_Cell_wise",
            "H3k9ac_Cell_wise",
            "H3k9me3_Cell_wise",
            "H4k20me1_Cell_wise")
path = system.file("extdata/rawdata", package = "OMICsPCAdata")

### reading data into OMICsdata object
InputOMICs(name = "OMICsdata", Assays = Assays, typeisfile = TRUE,
path = path)

 

3.3 Subsetting into groups

once the the dataframes corresponding to the Assays/factors are prepared, User may want to divide the entire annotation set into smaller groups. Here we we show an example to divide 154301 GENCODE TSS groups into 4 expression groups. The grouping criteria is based on the on/off status (determined from CAGE experiments) of the TSSsin 31 cell lines.

OMICsPCA has a function create_group() to do this task. This function takes the following 4 arguments:

  1. group_names : a vector containing the user defined names of the groups to be created

  2. factor : name of the data frame on which groups will be created

  3. comparison : a vector of comparison symbols such as >, <, ==, >=, <=, %in% etc

  4. condition : a vector of conditions corresponding to comparison. condition should be a vector or range of digits (e.g. c(1,3,7,9) or 1:5) if %in% is chosen as comparison and a single digit for other cases.

  5. name : name of the S4 object containing the assay data

  6. grouping_factor : name of the dataframe on which grouping will be done

create_group(name = "OMICsdata", group_names = c("WE" ,"RE" ,"NE" ,"IntE"),
grouping_factor = "CAGE_Cell_wise_v2",
comparison = c(">=" ,"%in%" ,"==" ,"%in%"),
condition = c("25" ,"1:5" ,"0" ,"6:24"))

In the above example the dataframe CAGE_Cell_wise_v2 is divided into 4 smaller data frames WE, RE, NE and IntE. “WE” contains TSSs expressed in >= 25 cell lines, “RE” represents TSSs expressed in 1 to 5 cell lines and so on.

The CAGE data frame looks like this:

A549 AG04450 B.Cells_CD20. BJ Gm12878
ENST00000387347.2 0 0 85.8895806558477 0 0
ENST00000387314.1 49.6336910685519 0 0 0 0
ENST00000389680.2 0 0 0 0 0
ENST00000386347.1 61.4568108749758 19.4710468352727 23.969601604456 17.9526438211874 129.285323659344
ENST00000361390.2 196.720325095994 121.562481593189 216.782580604901 60.083445046716 74.770012182987

NOTE: Running create_group is mandatory for all downstream analyses, even if there is no need to subset any assay to smaller groups. In such a case, choose the following:

name = name of the “OMICS”" object group_names = “all” grouping factor = name of any Assay used in “InputOMICs” comparison = “>=” condition = “0”

create_group() stores the smaller dataframes corresponding to the user defined groups in the groups slot of OMICsdata.

create_group() can also read predefined groups. The predefined groups should be supplied as a data frame of single column(containing the group names) and with row names through the argument groupinfo and the predefinedgroups argument should be set to “TRUE”.

path <- system.file("extdata/groupinfo", package = "OMICsPCAdata")

groupinfo <- read.table(file = path, header = TRUE, row.names = 1,
sep ="\t", comment.char = "", stringsAsFactors = FALSE, quote = "")

head(groupinfo)
# # A tibble: 6 x 1
#   group
# * <chr>
# 1 WE   
# 2 WE   
# 3 WE   
# 4 WE   
# 5 WE   
# 6 WE

create_group(name = "OMICsdata", predefinedgroups = TRUE,
groupinfo = groupinfo)

   

3.4 Exploratory data analysis (EDA) on created groups

Once the group information is read, we can study the the distribution of various Assays/factors(e.g. H2az, H3k9ac etc) on the annotations (e.g. TSSs, genes) of various groups (In the above example, the groups are created on the basis of on-off state of TSSs in 31 cell lines). OMICsPCA has several functions for EDA.

3.4.1 descriptor()

Descriptor works in two modes depending on the value passed through the argument choice. choice = 1 displays panels of boxplots corresponding to the Assay(s) or factor(s) chosen through argument factor. Each panel shows number of boxplots corresponding to the group(s) passed through argument groups. Each boxplot in choice 1 represents the disdribution of percentage of cell lines corresponding to a group that are overlapped with the selected assay.

NOTE : in groups, one group name should be put only once. NOTE : groups can handle only the groups created by “create_group()”

descriptor(name = "OMICsdata",
factors = c("CpG_methylation_Cell_wise", "DHS_len_Cell_wise",
"H2az_Cell_wise","H3k27ac_Cell_wise","H3k27me3_Cell_wise",
"H3k4me1_Cell_wise","H3k4me2_Cell_wise","H3k4me3_Cell_wise",
"H3k79me2_Cell_wise","H3k9ac_Cell_wise", "H3k9me3_Cell_wise",
"H4k20me1_Cell_wise"),
groups = c("WE","RE","NE","IntE"),
choice = 1, title = "Distribution of percentage of cell types overlapping
with various factors")

 

Above boxplot shows that “H2az”,“H3k27ac”,“H3k4me2”,“H3k4me3”,“H3k79me2” and “H3k9ac” overlaps with Widely Expressed (“WE”) TSSs in almost 100 % cell lines of respective assays. Thus they can be though of as characteristics of “WE”. In addition, almost the opposite trait is observed in “NE”, which in turn indicates that these 6 properties may be the discriminatory factors between the various expression groups.  

In choice = 2, a value needs to be supplied to the argument choice2group. This value should be the name of one of the groups created by “create_group()”. The plot displayed in this mode represents the distribution of percentage of celllines corresponding to a factor/Assay with various combination of otherAssays/ factors supplied through factors.

descriptor(name = "OMICsdata",
factors = c("CpG_methylation_Cell_wise", "DHS_len_Cell_wise",
"H2az_Cell_wise","H3k27ac_Cell_wise","H3k27me3_Cell_wise",
"H3k4me1_Cell_wise","H3k4me2_Cell_wise","H3k4me3_Cell_wise",
"H3k79me2_Cell_wise","H3k9ac_Cell_wise", "H3k9me3_Cell_wise",
"H4k20me1_Cell_wise"), groups = c("WE","RE", "IntE","NE"),
choice = 2,
choice2group = "WE", 
title = "Distribution of percentage of cell types overlapping with
a factor in various combinations of epigenetic marks in the
selected group")

 

The above set of boxplots indicates that most of the epigenetic factors in Widely expressed TSSs (“WE”) are present with other factors, except CpG methylation (leftmost boxplot of uppermost and leftmost panel). This gives us an indication of interplay between various epigenetic marks  

3.4.2 chart_correlation()

This function creates pairwise correlation and scatter plots and histogram on selected groups. The type of results should be passed through the argument choice. This is a wrapper on various functions and thus can take additional and non-conflicting arguments specific to them.  

Summary of choices
choice functions output
table cor {stats} correlation table
scatter pairs {graphics} scatterplot of each pair
hist ggplot,geom_histogram,facet_wrap{ggplot2} histogram of each column
all chart.Correlation {PerformanceAnalytics} all of the above together

 

groups <- c("WE")
chart_correlation(name = "OMICsdata", Assay = "H2az_Cell_wise",
groups = "WE", choice = "scatter")

 

All the correlation scatterplots of TSSs in “WE” looks similar shaped except the ones coming from Hepg2. This is an indication that H2az pattern on “WE”s are different than other 4 cell lines.

The correlation value between each pair of cell lines may be calculated by choice = table. The slight difference in Hepg2 is visible here also.

chart_correlation(name = "OMICsdata", Assay = "H2az_Cell_wise",
groups = "WE", choice = "table")

The diversion of hepg2 is more evident when plotted as histogram. The mode of “WE” is close to 0 in Hepg2 compared to other cell lines. This indicates that most of the “WE” in Hepg2 do not have H2az marks on them.  

chart_correlation(name = "OMICsdata", Assay = "H2az_Cell_wise",
groups = "WE", choice = "hist", bins = 10)

 

All the above 3 plots can be plotted in a single plot

chart_correlation(name = "OMICsdata", Assay = "H2az_Cell_wise",
groups = "WE", choice = "all")

 

3.5 Integration of Multiple Cell lines

If an assay (e.g. ChIP-seq for the histone modification H3k9ac) is done on multiple cells/conditions/treatment/time, it might be, sometimes, necessary to integrate or combine them, in order to understand the source of variation or to calculate a common metric to be served as the representative of all variables etc. Such combination may be done by several techniques like Principal Component Analysis (PCA) or Factor Analysis (FA). PCAOMICsPCA has a function integrate_variables() to integrate data from multiple cells or conditions using PCA.

integrate_variables() takes 3 mandatory inputs:

  1. factor : name of data frames similar to the ones created by prepareDataset().

An example of such data frame is given below:

head(H3k4me1_Cell_wise[177:179,1:5])
# # A tibble: 3 x 5
#   Gm12878 H1hesc  Hmec  Hsmm Hsmmt
# *   <dbl>  <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
# 1    0      0     0     0     0   
# 2    0      0     0     0     0   
# 3    5.37   6.76  7.39  7.84  7.49

 

  1. name : a vector containing the names of the groups created by create_groups() . e.g.

  2. groups : full set or subset of groups created by create_group(). The group names should be provided as vector string. e.g. c(“WE” ,“RE”)

integrate_variables() subsets the input dataframe into another dataframe according to the groups argument and integrates all columns of the sub data frame using PCA. This function is a wrapper around the function PCA() from package FactoMineR and thus can take additional arguments specific to the function PCA()

In this example we supply two more additional arguments scale.unit = FALSE and graph = FALSE

The combined data is stored in the PCA slot of the “OMICs” object.

integrate_variables(Assays = c("H2az_Cell_wise","H3k4me1_Cell_wise",
"H3k9ac_Cell_wise"), name = "OMICsdata",
groups = c("WE","RE", "NE", "IntE"), scale.unit = FALSE, graph = FALSE)

 

3.6 Analysis of of integrated data

The analyse_vaiables() function is designed for a quick analysis and visualization of the data integrated by integrate() function. It takes 3 compulsory arguments 1) name, 2) Assay and 3) choice . The type of analysis should be selected through the choice argument. This function acts as a wrapper around a collection of functions of package “factoextra”and “corrplot” and thus can take additional arguments specific and non-conflicting to such functions. Types of analysis and their corresponding input in choice is listed below:

Note: PC argument is mandatory for choice 4 and 5.

  83.3 % of variation is captured by PC1 alone, which indicates that 5 cell lines are very similar to one another. However, there may be the influence of huge number of ] “NE” (see integrate_variables() step). Therefore this analysis might be worth of doing on each individual expression group.

Loadings of each variable (here the cell lines) explains the intensity of their correlation with principal components. In the above plot the loading is expressed as the contribution of each cell lineson PC 1 and 2. Although the contribution of K562 is very high in PC1, its direction indicates its strong correlation with other PCs (PC2). On the other hand Hmec, Huvec, Nha, Nhek and Osteobl are highly correlated only with PC1. The small value (hence the small arrows) of contribution of other cell lines with PC1 indicates they might be correlated with other PCs also. This is more clearly explained when the plot is studies with the table generated by this command simultaneously.

3.8 Density analysis

The scatter plot of data points (here, rows/TSSs/individuals) may be highly disorganized. In such a situation, we may take the help of density functions to understand the overall structure of the dataset.


#### extracting coordinates of TSSs randomly (rand = 1000)
## The description of "extract()" is given at the Cluster
## analysis section (section X).
data <- extract(name = "OMICsdata", PC = c(1:4),
groups = c("WE","RE"), integrated = FALSE,
Assay = "H2az_Cell_wise", rand = 10000)

## scatterplot on PC1 and 2
plot(data[,1:2])

Once the cell lines of an assay are integrated into PCs, we may check the density distribution of scores on various principal components. OMICsPCA has a function plot_desnity() to calculate and plot the density distribution of PC scores. This function uses ggplot(), geom_density() and other additional functions from package ggplot2. Additional arugents of geom_density (e.g. adjust) may be also supplied through this function. The returned value is an “gg,ggplot” object.

Such kind of analysis may help us to choose factors (e.g. H2az, H3k4me1) that can discriminate between various groups (e.g. our expression groups “WE”, “RE”, “NE” and “IntE”).

NOTE : the groups argument should not contain any groups names that are not used in integrate

3.9 Integration of multiple assays

Once the discriminatory Assays between the groups are identified by previous analyses, we may integrate all such assays together.

Assays = c("H2az_Cell_wise", "H3k9ac_Cell_wise")

In this process it is possible to observe that some variables (Cell lines) are not similar to others and thus can be excluded :

exclude <- list(0,c(1,9))

The length of the list “exclude” should be equal to the Number of assays (i.e. length of “Assays”“). If no columns are selected for exclusion, a”0" should be placed in the “exclude” list. In the above example, we are excluding none of the columns from “H2az_Cell_wise” and column 1 and 9 from “H3k9ac_Cell_wise”

The integration of multiple assays is handled by integrateAssays function in OMICsPCA. It works in 2 modes:

  1. runs PCA on selected groups created by create_group() function

  2. runs PCA on all individuals (e.g. annotations: gene, TSS etc.)

The type of merging the assays should be entered by the argument mergetype

integrateAssays() returns a list containing the start and end column of each Assay in the integrated Assay

start_end <- integrateAssays(Assays = c("H2az_Cell_wise",
"H3k9ac_Cell_wise"), name = "OMICsdata", mergetype = 2,
exclude = exclude, graph = FALSE)

if mergetype is set to 1, then integrateAssays asks for the name of groups to be integrated.

Enter a vector of strings containing group names:

Here is an example of the allowed input

Enter a vector of strings containing group names: c("WE","RE")

 

3.10 Analysis of integrated data

All the analyses on variables and individuals of integrated Assays are designed to be done by the functions analyse_integrated_variables() and analyse_integrated_individuals(). These functions works similary as analyse_variables() and analyse_individuals() described in section VI and VII. The only difference between the analyses in section VI and VI is that, in those sectiones multiple cell lines from a single type of assay were integrated. Whereas, the analyses described in this section will be on multiple assays.

 

3.10.1 Analyses of variables

The extra argument needs to be supplied in analyse_integrated_variables() is start_end which is the returned value by integrateAssays().

The Assay argument works little bit differently here. it takes the the number corresponding to the order of assays used in the Assays argument of integrateAssays(). For example, in the above example Assays = c(“H2az_Cell_wise”, “H3k9ac_Cell_wise”). So here Assay = 1 indicates to “H2az_Cell_wise” and 2 = “H3k9ac_cell_wise”

The default argument set to Assay is “all”, which show analyses on full integrated assays. Here are some examples:

3.11 Cluster Analysis

The principal components obtained by combining multiple assays represents overall epigenetic state of each annotation (here TSSs). Our next objective is to find out groups of similar TSSs in terms of combined epigenetic state. We will use suitable clustering technique(s) to accomplish this job.

There are various clustering techniques exists available, each designed to perform specific tasks. Most of the partition based clustering algorithms needs the number of clusters as an input. From our density analysis we observed two dense regions in the data space of PC1 and PC2, which suggests that the number of clusters should be set at 2. However, there are shophisticated indices designed to validate the number of clusters.

OMICsPCA has a function “cluster_parameters()” to perform this job. It runs two algorithms “clvalid” and “NbClust” in background, which in turn use different set of validation techniques to decide number of clusters.

“cluster_parameters()” extracts data from the “OMICs” object supplied through name argument via the “extract()” function. Both the algorithms used in “cluster_parameters()” function takes huge memory and cpu for higher number of samples. Therefore, it is recommended to used a subset of original data while running this function. A subset of rows can be selected randomly through the rand argument of “extract()”. User may also chose whether to use integrated assays or non integrated assays through the logical argument integrated of function “extract()”.

data <- extract(name = "OMICsdata", PC = c(1:4),
groups = c("WE","RE"), integrated = TRUE, rand = 600)

“cluster_parameters()” uses the output of “extract()” and runs one of the algorithm between “clvalid” or “NbClust” to determine number of clusters.

The parametrs of “clvalid” and “NbClust” are passed through the clusteringMethods, validationMethods and distance argument of “cluster_parameters()” function. The argument pairs are different in “NbClust” and “clvalid” and thus should be chosen carefully.


#### Using "clValid" ####

clusterstats <- cluster_parameters(name = data,
optimal = FALSE, n = 2:6, comparisonAlgorithm = "clValid",
distance = "euclidean", clusteringMethods = c("kmeans","pam"),
validationMethods = c("internal","stability"))

Now, depending on the output of “cluster_parameters()”, we may choose the appropriate clustering algorithm and number of clusters.

OMICsPCA has the function “cluster()” designed for the clustering task. “cluster()” has many clustering options which should be chosen through choice argument. The class of the returned value by “cluster()” depends on the type of clustering method chosen. So, extraction and visualization of data from cluster objects are different for different choices.  


data <- extract(name = "OMICsdata", PC = c(1:4),
groups = c("WE","RE"), integrated = TRUE, rand = 1000)

library(factoextra)

### kmeans clustering

clusters <- cluster(name = data, n = 2, choice = "kmeans",
title = "kmeans on 2 clusters")

# visualisation of clusters

print(clusters$plot)


# in 3D
clustered_data <- cbind(data,clusters$cluster$cluster)
plot3d(data[,1:3], col = clusters$cluster$cluster)

### density-based clustering

clusters <- cluster(name = data, choice = "density",
eps = 2, MinPts = 100, graph = TRUE,
title = "eps = 1 and MinPts = 1.5")

# visualisation of clusters
print(clusters$plot)


# in 3D
clustered_data <- as.data.frame(cbind(data,clusters$cluster$cluster))

#removing unclustered points
clustered_data <- clustered_data[clustered_data$V5 != 0, ]

library(rgl)
#plotting clusters on first 3 PCs
plot3d(clustered_data[,1:3], col = clustered_data$V5)
